+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Eto8UH4m7JFazafSLvk9vb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All pass. Let me also think about whether the `findGateWithInput` function might find the wrong gate in some cases. It returns the first matching gate. If there are multiple XOR gates with the same input, it could return the wrong one.\n\nFor example, at bit 2 looking for `findGateWithInput('XOR', carry=c01)`. There could be the sum XOR at bit 2 (`t02 XOR c01`) and... actually, in a correct adder, each wire is used as input by at most 2 gates (XOR and AND at the same bit). And carry is used by exactly one XOR and one AND gate. So `findGateWithInput('XOR', carry)` should return the correct gate.\n\nBut what if carry was swapped with another wire that IS used by multiple XOR gates? In a correct adder, only the first-level XOR outputs (t_i) are used by multiple gates. And x_i, y_i are each used by two gates (XOR and AND). Other wires are used by 1-2 gates. So the risk of ambiguity is low.\n\nLet me also think about performance. The problem says circuits with up to 45 input bits (~220 gates) and must return in under 5 seconds. My algorithm iterates bit by bit (O(N) where N is number of bits). For each bit, buildIndexes() is O(G) where G is number of gates. And findGateWithInput is O(G). In the worst case, we rebuild indexes multiple times per bit. So the total complexity is roughly O(N * G * swaps_per_bit). With N=45 and G=220, this is well under 5 seconds.\n\nActually, buildIndexes() is called on every bit regardless of swaps, since I have `let { byOutput, byInputs } = buildIndexes()` at the start of each bit. I could optimize this, but it's not necessary for the given constraints.\n\nLet me now make sure everything builds and lints cleanly."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":192,"cache_read_input_tokens":99204,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_in